aSTART-L also included a Ph+ ALL cohort, data not reported hereA series of phase II trials, the pivotal START (SRCβ€“ABL Tyrosine kinase inhibition Activity Research Trials) trial program (TableΒ 1), followed the phase I dose-escalation study. The primary objective for these trials was to treat patients with resistance or intolerance to imatinib who therefore had a life-threatening medical need. As the pharmacokinetics of the dasatinib 70Β mg twice-daily regimen were better understood, it was selected as the preferred dosing option in these patients. These open-label, multicenter trials established the efficacy and safety of second-line dasatinib (70Β mg twice daily) in the treatment of imatinib-resistant or imatinib-intolerant patients with CML (all phases) or Ph+ ALL. Data from this program led to the initial approval of dasatinib in these indications.Two START studies assessed second-line dasatinib 70Β mg twice daily in patients with CML-CP. START-C was a single-arm study, and START-R was a randomized, parallel-arm study of dasatinib versus high-dose imatinib (800Β mg/day) in patients resistant to standard dose imatinib (Hochhaus et al. 2007, 2008; Kantarjian et al. 2007, 2009a; Mauro et al. 2008). In START-C (NΒ =Β 387), dasatinib induced MCyR (primary end point) in 62Β % of patients after a minimum follow-up of 24Β months (Mauro et al. 2008). The corresponding CCyR rate was 53Β %. In START-R, rates of MCyR were 53Β % in the dasatinib 70Β mg twice-daily arm (nΒ =Β 101) and 33Β % in the high-dose imatinib arm (nΒ =Β 49) (pΒ =Β 0.017) after a minimum follow-up of 24Β months (Kantarjian et al. 2009a). CCyR rates were 44 and 18Β %, respectively (pΒ =Β 0.0025). Although no formal statistical comparison between the study arms was planned, the data suggested relatively greater efficacy for dasatinib compared with imatinib (Kantarjian et al. 2009a). These responses were also durable, as a pooled analysis (NΒ =Β 387) of the START-C and START-R studies showed that 90Β % of patients achieving a CCyR maintained this level of response after 24Β months (Baccarani et al. 2008). START-A, START-B, and START-L were single-arm studies of second-line dasatinib 70Β mg twice daily in patients with CML-AP, CML-BP, and CML-BP/Ph+Β ALL, respectively (Apperley et al. 2009; Cortes et al. 2007a, 2008; Guilhot et al. 2007; Ottmann et al. 2007; Saglio et al. 2008). In the START-A trial (NΒ =Β 174), after a median follow-up of 14.1Β months, 64Β % of patients with CML-AP achieved the primary end point of MHR and 45Β % achieved a CHR (Apperley et al. 2009). START-B included patients with myeloid CML-BP (NΒ =Β 109), and START-L included patients with lymphoid CML-BP (nΒ =Β 48) and a subset of patients with Ph+Β ALL (Cortes et al. 2007a). After a minimum follow-up of 24Β months, a CHR was achieved in 26Β % of patients with myeloid CML-BP and in 29Β % of patients with lymphoid CML-BP (Saglio et al. 2008).The recommended starting dose for dasatinib in patients with CML-CP is now 100Β mg once daily (EMA SprycelΒ® [dasatinib] 2012; SprycelΒ® BMS 2013) following the results of a phase III dose-optimization study showing that 100Β mg once daily was associated with similar efficacy as the twice-daily regimen, but with a reduction in toxicity (Shah et al. 2008a). Although the dasatinib half-life of 3β€“5Β h (SprycelΒ® BMS 2013) was used as a basis for the initial twice-daily dosing regimen, transient exposure of CML cell lines to dasatinib in vitro has been demonstrated to induce apoptosis (Shah et al. 2008b), supporting the feasibility of once-daily dosing, and data from the phase I study suggested that once-daily and twice-daily dose schedules were associated with similar response rates (Talpaz et al. 2006). Furthermore, due to dose reductions in the START-C and START-R studies, the median total daily dose delivered to patients approximated 100Β mg/day (Hochhaus et al. 2007; Kantarjian et al. 2007). It was therefore proposed to compare the 100Β mg once-daily dose with other schedules. In this dose-optimization study, patients (NΒ =Β 670) were randomized to receive dasatinib at 100Β mg once daily (nΒ =Β 167), 140Β mg once daily (nΒ =Β 167), 50Β mg twice daily (nΒ =Β 168), or 70Β mg twice daily (nΒ =Β 168) (Shah et al. 2008a). After a minimum follow-up of 2Β years, rates of CCyR and MMR were similar across the different dosing schedules (CCyR 50β€“54Β %; MMR 37β€“38Β %) (Shah et al. 2010). In the 100Β mg once-daily arm, the 24-month rates of CCyR and MMR were 50 and 37Β %, respectively. Rates of progression-free survival (PFS), overall survival (OS), and transformation to AP/BP by 24Β months were 80, 91, and 3Β %, respectively (TableΒ 2). The 100Β mg once-daily arm was associated with improved safety. Rates of all-grade pleural effusion (pΒ =Β 0.049), gradeΒ β‰¥3 thrombocytopenia (pΒ =Β 0.003), all-grade neutropenia (pΒ =Β 0.034), and all-grade leukocytopenia (pΒ =Β 0.017) were significantly lower for patients treated with dasatinib 100Β mg once daily compared with other schedules (Shah et al. 2010). After a minimum follow-up of 5Β years, PFS, OS, and rates of transformation to AP/BP were 57, 78, and 5Β %, respectively, in the 100Β mg once-daily arm (Shah et al. 2012). TableΒ 2Efficacy data from the CA180-034 phase III dose-optimization study of second-line dasatinib in patients with CML-CP resistant or intolerant to imatinib therapy after a minimum follow-up of 2Β years (Shah et al. 2008a, 2010)Dasatinib dose schedule
