aDefinition of disease progression: loss of previous CHR or MCyR, confirmed AP/BP disease, increasing WBC count (recorded by the investigator as a doubling from the lowest value to >20,000/mm3 or increases of >50,000/mm3 on 2 assessments β‰¥2Β weeks apart), increase in Ph+Β metaphases by β‰¥30Β %, or death from any causeA similar phase III dose-optimization study in patients with CML-AP (Kantarjian et al. 2009b) and CML-BP (Saglio et al. 2010b) led to a recommended dasatinib dose of 140Β mg once daily in these indications (EMA SprycelΒ® [dasatinib] 2012; SprycelΒ® BMS 2013). Patients were randomized to receive dasatinib 70Β mg twice daily (nΒ =Β 159, AP; nΒ =Β 74, myeloid BP [MBP]; nΒ =Β 28, lymphoid BP [LBP]) or 140 mg once daily (nΒ =Β 158, AP; nΒ =Β 75 MBP; nΒ =Β 33, LBP). In patients with CML-AP, similar rates of MHR (68 vs 66Β %) and MCyR (43 vs 39Β %) were observed in both treatment arms after a median follow-up of 15Β months. Significantly, fewer patients in the once-daily arm had pleural effusion compared with the twice-daily arm (pΒ <Β 0.001) (Kantarjian et al. 2009b). After 2Β years of follow-up, for patients with myeloid BP, the MHR rates in both arms were 28Β %; for those with lymphoid BP, the corresponding rates were 42Β % in the once-daily arm and 32Β % in the twice-daily arm. AE rates were suggestive of improved safety for dasatinib 140Β mg once daily (Saglio et al. 2010b).Early responses to dasatinib 100 mg once daily in the treatment for newly diagnosed CML-CPFollowing the success of second-line dasatinib in treating patients with CML, trials were performed to assess the clinical benefit of this agent in the first-line setting. The rationale for performing first-line studies derives partly from the observation that earlier responses to therapy are associated with better outcomes as seen with first-line imatinib (de Lavallade et al. 2008; Druker et al. 2006; Kantarjian et al. 2008; Marin et al. 2008). Similarly, in a retrospective analysis of patients from the dasatinib START-C and START-R, and dose-optimization trials, patients who achieved CCyR at 12Β months had a 24-month PFS rate of 97Β % (95Β % confidence interval [CI],Β 93β€“100Β %) compared with 78Β % (95Β % CI, 72β€“83Β %) for patients who did not achieve CCyR or MMR at this time point (Hochhaus et al. 2009b). In exploratory landmark analyses of the second-line dasatinib dose-optimization study, patients receiving dasatinib 100Β mg once daily with cytogenetic assessments at 12Β months showing achievement of CCyR had higher PFS after 4-year minimum follow-up compared with patients achieving less than partial CyR (PCyR) responses (87 vs 45Β %) (Shah et al. 2011). With 5-year follow-up, similar trends were observed for patients achievingΒ β‰¤10Β % BCRβ€“ABL levels compared to patients with >10Β % BCRβ€“ABL levels at 3Β months (Shah et al. 2012). These landmark analyses demonstrate the importance of achieving an early response to improve patient outcome. Furthermore, dasatinib is more potent than imatinib, and less susceptible to mechanisms of imatinib resistance. Therefore, it may be expected to elicit earlier responses than imatinib with consequently improved long-term outcomes.The first trial investigating dasatinib as first-line treatment was a phase II, open-label study (Cortes et al. 2010b). Patients with newly diagnosed CML-CP were randomized to receive dasatinib 100Β mg once daily (nΒ =Β 66) or 50Β mg twice daily (nΒ =Β 33) (Pemmaraju et al. 2011). Because of results from a phase III multinational randomized study of first-line dasatinib and trends in favor of the 100Β mg once-daily schedule of dasatinib seen in this study and others, the 50Β mg twice-daily arm of this trial was closed after 66 patients were enrolled, and all subsequent patients were randomized to the 100Β mg once-daily arm. The study continues enrolling patients in the once-daily arm (Cortes et al. 2010b; Pemmaraju et al. 2011). After a median follow-up of 29Β months, in patients withΒ β‰¥3-month follow-up (nΒ =Β 87), rates of CCyR and MMR were 95 and 86Β %, respectively. BCRβ€“ABL levels of β‰¤0.0032Β % (β‰¥4.5-log reduction; MR4.5) were achieved in 67Β % of patients. Responses were achieved rapidly with 94 and 95Β % of patients achieving a CCyR after 6 and 12Β months, respectively. Similarly, MMR rates at 6 and 12Β months were 68 and 73Β %, respectively. These data compare favorably with historic response data for imatinib (Pemmaraju et al. 2011).Dasatinib in the first-line setting was further investigated in the pivotal, open-label, multinational, randomized phase III trial of Dasatinib versus Imatinib Study in Treatment-NaΓ―ve CML Patients (DASISION) (Kantarjian et al. 2010). In this study, 519 patients newly diagnosed with CML-CP were randomized to receive dasatinib 100Β mg once daily (nΒ =Β 259) or imatinib 400Β mg once daily (nΒ =Β 260) (FigureΒ 1) (Kantarjian et al. 2010). Efficacy data are shown in TableΒ 3. The primary end point of this study was confirmed CCyR (cCCyR; CCyR on two consecutive assessments) by 12Β months. For the dasatinib versus imatinib arms, the rate of cCCyR by 12Β months was 77 versus 66Β % (pΒ =Β 0.007), respectively (Kantarjian et al. 2010). Cumulative CCyR, MMR, and MR4.5 rates were higher for dasatinib across a 24-month period (pΒ =Β 0.0002, pΒ <Β 0.0001, and pΒ =Β 0.002, respectively) (Kantarjian et al. 2012). Responses to dasatinib were rapid and prolonged; median times to CCyR were 3.2 and 6.0Β months and median times to MMR were 15 and 36Β months in the dasatinib and imatinib arms, respectively (Kantarjian et al. 2012). At 24Β months, for dasatinib versus imatinib, cumulative rates of MMR were 64 versus 46Β % (pΒ <Β 0.0001), rates for BCRβ€“ABLΒ β‰¤Β 0.01Β % (MR4) were 29 versus 19Β % (pΒ =Β 0.0053), and rates of MR4.5 were 17 versus 8Β % (pΒ =Β 0.0032) (Hochhaus et al. 2012a; Kantarjian et al. 2012). After 2-year follow-up, transformation to AP/BP throughout study follow-up (including on study and after discontinuation) occurred in nine patients (3.5Β %) receiving dasatinib and 15 (5.8Β %) receiving imatinib (Hochhaus et al. 2012a; Kantarjian et al. 2012). At 2-year follow-up, survival data for this study remain immature, but no difference was observed between dasatinib and imatinib for PFS (93.7 and 92.1Β %) and OS (95.3 and 95.2Β %). A small difference in failure-free survival for dasatinib versus imatinib was observed (including protocol defined progression; 91.2 vs 87.8Β %) (Hochhaus et al. 2012a; Kantarjian et al. 2012).
